HOUSE BILL 423
F3 6lr1027
By: Prince George’s County Delegation
Introduced and read first time: January 22, 2026
Assigned to: Ways and Means
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
House action: Adopted
Read second time: March 7, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Prince George’s County – Public High Schools – Drug Detection Products
3 PG 501–26
4 FOR the purpose of requiring, subject to certain conditions, the Prince George’s County
5 Board of Education to provide certain drug detection products to public high school
6 students in the county in a certain manner beginning in a certain school year;
7 requiring each public high school in the county to submit a certain report to
8 Maryland’s Office of Overdose Response on or before a certain date each year; and
9 generally relating to drug detection products and Prince George’s County public high
10 schools.
11 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
12 Article – Education
13 Section 7–426.5(f)(1)
14 Annotated Code of Maryland
15 (2025 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
16 BY adding to
17 Article – Education
18 Section 7–455
19 Annotated Code of Maryland
20 (2025 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *hb0423*

2 HOUSE BILL 423
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article – Education
4 7–426.5.
5 (f) (1) On or before October 1 each year, each public school shall submit, on
6 the form that the Department requires, a report to the Department on each incident at the
7 school that required the use of naloxone or other overdose–reversing medication.
8 7–455.
9 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
10 INDICATED.
11 (2) “DRINK SPIKING DETECTION PRODUCT” MEANS A PRODUCT THAT
12 HAS ONE OR MORE TEST SPOTS THAT ALLOW THE USER TO TEST A PORTION OF A
13 BEVERAGE TO DETERMINE WHETHER THE BEVERAGE HAS BEEN CONTAMINATED
14 WITH THE DRUG GAMMA–HYDROXYBUTYRIC ACID (GHB) OR KETAMINE.
15 (3) “DRUG DETECTION STRIP” MEANS A DISPOSABLE TEST STRIP
16 THAT ALLOWS AN INDIVIDUAL TO TEST A DRUG FOR THE PRESENCE OF FENTANYL.
17 (B) THIS SECTION APPLIES ONLY IN PRINCE GEORGE’S COUNTY.
18 (C) BEGINNING IN THE 2026–2027 SCHOOL YEAR, THE PRINCE GEORGE’S
19 COUNTY BOARD OF EDUCATION SHALL REQUIRE EACH PUBLIC HIGH SCHOOL IN
20 THE COUNTY TO PROVIDE, AT NO CHARGE TO STUDENTS, DRINK SPIKING DETECTION
21 PRODUCTS AND DRUG DETECTION STRIPS
22 (1) IT IS THE INTENT OF THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY THAT THE PUBLIC
23 HIGH SCHOOLS IN PRINCE GEORGE’S COUNTY PROVIDE DRINK SPIKING DETECTION
24 PRODUCTS AND DRUG DETECTION STRIPS TO THEIR STUDENTS.
25 (2) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (3) OF THIS SUBSECTION, BEGINNING IN
26 THE 2026–2027 SCHOOL YEAR, THE PRINCE GEORGE’S COUNTY BOARD OF
27 EDUCATION SHALL REQUIRE EACH PUBLIC HIGH SCHOOL IN THE COUNTY TO
28 PROVIDE, AT NO COST TO STUDENTS:
29 (I) DRINK SPIKING DETECTION PRODUCTS; AND
30 (II) DRUG DETECTION STRIPS, IF A PUBLIC HIGH SCHOOL IN
31 THE COUNTY REPORTS AN INCIDENT AT THE SCHOOL REQUIRING THE USE OF

HOUSE BILL 423 3
1 NALOXONE OR OTHER OVERDOSE–REVERSING MEDICATION IN ACCORDANCE WITH
2 § 7–426.5(F)(1) OF THIS SUBTITLE.
3 (3) PUBLIC HIGH SCHOOLS IN THE COUNTY ARE REQUIRED TO
4 PROVIDE DRINK SPIKING DETECTION PRODUCTS AND DRUG DETECTION STRIPS IN
5 ACCORDANCE WITH PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION ONLY IF THE PRODUCTS
6 ARE PROVIDED TO THE PUBLIC HIGH SCHOOLS AT NO COST TO THE SCHOOLS.
7 (D) THE DRINK SPIKING DETECTION PRODUCTS AND DRUG DETECTION
8 STRIPS REQUIRED TO BE PROVIDED TO HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS UNDER THIS
9 SECTION MAY BE MADE AVAILABLE IN SCHOOL–BASED HEALTH CLINICS OR SCHOOL
10 LIBRARIES.
11 (E) ON OR BEFORE OCTOBER 1, 2027, AND EACH OCTOBER 1 THEREAFTER,
12 EACH PUBLIC HIGH SCHOOL IN THE COUNTY SHALL REPORT TO MARYLAND’S
13 OFFICE OF OVERDOSE RESPONSE ON THE QUANTITY OF DRUG DETECTION
14 PRODUCTS DISTRIBUTED BY THE SCHOOL DURING THE PREVIOUS SCHOOL YEAR.
15 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
16 1, 2026.
Approved:
